# Container and Host Interaction

## Communication Between Container and Host

Docker containers run in an isolated environment, but they can still interact with the host system in different ways.  
Below are common techniques used for communication between containers and the host.

---

# 1. Port Mapping

## Access Container Services from Host

```bash
# Run nginx container and map port
docker run -d -p 8080:80 --name webserver nginx

# Open in browser
http://localhost:8080
Mapping Multiple Ports
docker run -d \
  -p 8080:80 \
  -p 8443:443 \
  --name webserver \
  nginx

Example:

8080 → HTTP access

8443 → HTTPS access

Access Using Host IP

Containers can also be accessed from other machines on the same network.

http://host-ip:8080
http://192.168.1.100:8080
2. Volume Mounting (Sharing Files)
Mount Host Directory to Container
docker run -it -v $(pwd):/app ubuntu bash

Inside the container, /app contains the files from the host's current directory.

Create File in Container and Access from Host
docker run -it -v /tmp/mydata:/data ubuntu bash

# Inside container
echo "Hello from container" > /data/test.txt

On host system:

ls /tmp/mydata
cat /tmp/mydata/test.txt

The file is visible on both host and container.

Persistent Storage Example
docker run -d \
  --name mysql_db \
  -v mysql_data:/var/lib/mysql \
  -e MYSQL_ROOT_PASSWORD=secret \
  mysql

Even if the container is removed, the data stored in the volume remains safe.

3. Environment Variables
Pass Variables to Container
docker run -e COLLEGE=CSE -it ubuntu bash

Inside container:

echo $COLLEGE

Output:

CSE
Pass Multiple Variables
docker run \
  -e APP_NAME=myapp \
  -e LOG_LEVEL=debug \
  -e DB_HOST=localhost \
  -it ubuntu bash
Using Environment File

Create environment file:

echo "APP_NAME=myapp" > .env
echo "LOG_LEVEL=info" >> .env

Run container with environment file:

docker run --env-file .env -it ubuntu bash
4. Executing Commands in Containers
Enter Running Container
docker exec -it container_name /bin/bash
Execute Commands Without Opening Shell
docker exec container_name ls /
docker exec container_name pwd
Creating Files Inside Container
docker exec myapp mkdir /app
docker exec myapp bash -c 'echo "Hello Docker" > /app/data.txt'
docker exec myapp cat /app/data.txt
5. Container Networking
Communication Between Containers
docker network create mynetwork

Run containers on same network:

docker run -d --name web --network mynetwork nginx
docker run -d --name app --network mynetwork ubuntu sleep 1000

Test connection:

docker exec app ping web
Exposing Container Ports

Dockerfile example:

EXPOSE 8080

Run container:

docker run -d -p 8080:8080 myapp

Access service:

curl http://localhost:8080
6. Logs and Monitoring
View Container Logs
docker logs container_name

Follow logs in real time:

docker logs -f container_name

Show last 50 lines:

docker logs --tail 50 container_name

Logs with timestamps:

docker logs --timestamps container_name
Inspect Container
docker inspect container_name

Get container IP:

docker inspect -f '{{.NetworkSettings.IPAddress}}' container_name
Monitor Resource Usage
docker stats container_name

View stats for all containers:

docker stats
7. Copy Files Between Host and Container
Host → Container
docker cp local_file.txt container_name:/container/path/

Example:

docker cp index.html webserver:/usr/share/nginx/html/
Container → Host
docker cp container_name:/container/file.txt ./local_path/

Example:

docker cp webserver:/etc/nginx/nginx.conf ./backup/
Practical Examples
Example 1 – Local Web Development
docker run -d \
  --name dev_server \
  -p 8000:8000 \
  -v $(pwd):/app \
  -e DEBUG=true \
  python:3.9 \
  python -m http.server 8000 --directory /app

Files edited on host will automatically reflect inside the container.

Example 2 – Database with Persistent Storage
docker volume create pgdata

Run PostgreSQL:

docker run -d \
  --name postgres_db \
  -e POSTGRES_PASSWORD=secret \
  -v pgdata:/var/lib/postgresql/data \
  -p 5432:5432 \
  postgres:13

Data remains available even after container restart.

Quick Reference
Task	Command
Port mapping	docker run -p 8080:80 image
Mount directory	docker run -v /host:/container image
Set environment variable	docker run -e VAR=value image
Execute command	docker exec -it container cmd
View logs	docker logs container
Copy files	docker cp file container:/path
Create network	docker network create name
Container IP	docker inspect container

