# Container and Host Interaction

## Introduction

Docker containers usually run in an isolated environment.  
However, they can still communicate with the host system and other containers using several methods such as port mapping, volumes, environment variables, and networking.

This section explains how containers interact with the host machine.

---

# 1. Port Mapping

## Accessing Container Services from Host

Port mapping allows a container service to be accessed from the host system.

```bash
# Run nginx container and map port
docker run -d -p 8080:80 --name webserver nginx

Open in browser:

http://localhost:8080
Mapping Multiple Ports
docker run -d \
  -p 8080:80 \
  -p 8443:443 \
  --name webserver \
  nginx

Example:

8080 → HTTP

8443 → HTTPS

Access Using Host IP

Containers can also be accessed using the host machine’s IP address.

http://host-ip:8080
http://192.168.1.100:8080
2. Volume Mounting (Sharing Files)

Volumes allow file sharing between host and container.

Mount Host Directory
docker run -it -v $(pwd):/app ubuntu bash

Inside the container, /app will contain the files from the host directory.

Create File in Container and Access from Host
docker run -it -v /tmp/mydata:/data ubuntu bash

# Inside container
echo "Hello from container" > /data/test.txt

Check on host machine:

ls /tmp/mydata
cat /tmp/mydata/test.txt

The file is visible on both host and container.

Persistent Data Example
docker run -d \
  --name mysql_db \
  -v mysql_data:/var/lib/mysql \
  -e MYSQL_ROOT_PASSWORD=secret \
  mysql

The data stored in the volume remains even if the container is removed.

3. Environment Variables

Environment variables can be passed from the host to the container.

Pass Single Variable
docker run -e COLLEGE=CSE -it ubuntu bash

Check inside container:

echo $COLLEGE

Output:

CSE
Pass Multiple Variables
docker run \
  -e APP_NAME=myapp \
  -e LOG_LEVEL=debug \
  -e DB_HOST=localhost \
  -it ubuntu bash
Use Environment File

Create environment file:

echo "APP_NAME=myapp" > .env
echo "LOG_LEVEL=info" >> .env

Run container with env file:

docker run --env-file .env -it ubuntu bash
4. Container Execution

Containers can be interacted with by executing commands inside them.

Enter Container
docker exec -it container_name /bin/bash
Execute Commands
docker exec container_name ls /
docker exec container_name pwd
Create Files Inside Container
docker exec myapp mkdir /app
docker exec myapp bash -c 'echo "Hello Docker" > /app/data.txt'
docker exec myapp cat /app/data.txt
5. Docker Networking

Networking allows containers to communicate with each other.

Create Network
docker network create mynetwork
Run Containers in Same Network
docker run -d --name web --network mynetwork nginx
docker run -d --name app --network mynetwork ubuntu sleep 1000
Test Communication
docker exec app ping web

Containers on the same network can communicate using container names.

Expose Ports

Dockerfile example:

EXPOSE 8080

Run container:

docker run -d -p 8080:8080 myapp

Access service:

curl http://localhost:8080
6. Logs and Monitoring

Docker provides commands to view logs and monitor containers.

View Logs
docker logs container_name

Follow logs in real time:

docker logs -f container_name

Last 50 log lines:

docker logs --tail 50 container_name

Logs with timestamps:

docker logs --timestamps container_name
Inspect Container
docker inspect container_name

Get container IP:

docker inspect -f '{{.NetworkSettings.IPAddress}}' container_name
Monitor Resources
docker stats container_name

Monitor all containers:

docker stats
7. Copy Files Between Host and Container
Host to Container
docker cp local_file.txt container_name:/container/path/

Example:

docker cp index.html webserver:/usr/share/nginx/html/
Container to Host
docker cp container_name:/container/file.txt ./local_path/

Example:

docker cp webserver:/etc/nginx/nginx.conf ./backup/
